    <segment id="1" parent="15" relname="preparation">Intuitiveness in Design </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="17" relname="span">

According the The AmP6an HeritageÂ® Dictionary of the English Language, Intuitiveness is possessing or demonstrating intuition.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="36" relname="span"> 

In today&apos;s tech savvy world, the concept of intuitive design is no longer just a concept of perceptivity.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="19" relname="antithesis"> 

While designing new interfaces, 
the designers not only think of an inbuilt sixth sense for the application</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="26" relname="span"> but also try to provide additional functionality to make a product smarter.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="span"> 

I believe that this concept muddles this concept</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="18" relname="span"> cause it limits the target audience to non computer/net savvy customers.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="27" relname="span">

The customers of most application differ by the extent of PRE-knowledge they have or don&apos;t have.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> 

What may appear as intuitive to a designer of an application software or webpage may seem rather complicated to the novice user.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="antithesis"> 

Keeping a product just intuitive is not possible.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="35" relname="span"> 

It is essential to incorporate a sense of innate knowledge with smart knowledge.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="29" relname="span"> 

Sometimes it may be easier to do something in an interface in 5 steps than to use the so called built in intuitive functionality, </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="9" relname="elaboration">

it all depends on who is using the application.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="21" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> 

As the customers range from novice to experts,</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="23" relname="span"> 
so does the ability of an application to serve a balance.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="22" relname="concession"> 

Keeping it easy is always essential </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="30" relname="span">
but to cater to a broader more knowledgeble crowd, 
building quick shortcuts may be essential.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="32" relname="span"> 

A simple to use application such as MS Excel can be extremely confusing for those users who are not familiar with macro&apos;s and basic formulae.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="24" relname="concession"> 

There may be many ideas of intuitiveness built in, </segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="31" relname="span">
but the question of how to achieve a simple task may still be struggle for many. </segment>
